'''Horácio da Silva Roque''' (12 April 1944 &ndash; 19 May 2010) was a [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] [[financier]] and [[businessman]], who founded the [[Banco Internacional do Funchal]] (BANIF) in 1988.<ref name=pn>{{cite news |first=|last=|title=Banif bank founder Horácio Roque dies|url= http://www.theportugalnews.com/cgi-bin/article.pl?id=1062-6|work=[[The Portugal News]]|publisher= |date=2010-05-22 |accessdate=2010-05-30}}</ref>
Born in [[Oleiros Parish, Oleiros|Oleiros]], [[Oleiros Municipality, Portugal|Oleiros]], Roque started his first business, a [[Bar (establishment)|bar]] in [[Angola (Portugal)|Portuguese Angola]], then a [[Portuguese Empire|colonial possession of Portugal]], when he was just 17 years old.<ref name=pn/> He gradually built up his wealth from a series of [[Venture capital|business ventures]] throughout southern Africa.<ref name=pn/> In addition to the Banco Internacional do Funchal (BANIF), which is headquartered in [[Funchal]], [[Madeira]], Roque's assets included [[real estate]] and [[insurance]] holdings throughout Portugal, [[North America]] and [[South America]].<ref name=pn/>
Roque founded a foundation in 1991 to fund cultural, [[educational]] and other [[philanthropic]] causes.<ref name=pn/>
He married twice, firstly to Maria de Fátima Henriques da Silva Moura and secondly to Paula Caetano, without issue. By first marriage he had Maria Teresa Henriques da Silva Moura Roque, born in 1971, wife of Pietro Saviotti dal Fabbro, by whom she had issue, and Cristina Henriques da Silva Moura Roque, born in 1978.<ref>http://www.geneall.net/P/per_page.php?id=1173943 Horácio Roque in a Portuguese Genealogical site</ref>
Horácio Roque died of a [[stroke]] on 19 May 2010, at the Hospital of São José, at São José, in [[Lisbon]], Portugal. He was 66 years old.<ref name=pn/>
