{{COI|date=March 2018}} {{advert|date=March 2018}} {{Infobox person | name = Paolo Costagli | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1966 | birth_place = [[Florence]], [[Italy]] | death_date = | death_place = | residence = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S. | other_names = | occupation = [[Jewellery design]]er | years_active = 1991 – present<ref name="ny">{{cite web |url= http://nymag.com/listings/stores/paolo-costagli/ |title= Shopping: Paolo Costagli |publisher= [[New York (magazine)|New York]] |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100703032153/http://nymag.com/listings/stores/paolo-costagli/ |archivedate = 2010-07-03 |accessdate=2017-11-15}}</ref> | known_for = | education = [[Gemological Institute of America]] (1989), Collegio Alla Querce (1985) | notable_works = | website = {{URL|paolocostagli.com}} }}
'''Paolo Costagli''' (born in 1966) is an Italian [[jewellery design]]er and [[Gemology|gemologist]]. Costagli is known for using hard-to-find colored [[gemstone]]s,<ref name="treasure2013">{{cite web |url= http://robbreport.com/style/jewelry/paolo-costaglis-treasure-hunt-229565/ |title= Paolo Costagli’s Treasure Hunt |author = Jill Newman |date = 2013-09-15 |publisher= [[Robb Report]] |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171118072259/http://robbreport.com/style/jewelry/paolo-costaglis-treasure-hunt-229565/ |archivedate = 2017-11-18 |accessdate=2017-11-18}}</ref> sophisticated color combinations<ref name="epoch" /> and strong architectural shapes.<ref name="epoch" />
==Early life == Paolo Costagli was born in 1966 in Florence.<ref name="epoch">{{cite web |url= https://www.theepochtimes.com/paolo-costagli-finds-the-jewel-in-the-stone_662910.html |title= Paolo Costagli Finds the Jewel in the Stone |date = 2014-05-08 |author = Kati Vereshaka |publisher= [[Epoch Times]] |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171115211449/https://www.theepochtimes.com/paolo-costagli-finds-the-jewel-in-the-stone_662910.html |archivedate = 2016-12-01 |accessdate=2017-11-15}}</ref> He studied at the private school Collegio Alla Querce in Florence. After his military service{{elucidate|date=November 2017}} he moved to the [[United States]]<ref name="instoreint">{{cite web |url= https://www.instoremag.com/products/399-products-indesign/designer-profiles/12818-designing-lives-paolo-costagli#!AN_572_GIA_Fancy_Light_Yel |title= Designing Lives: Paolo Costagli |author = Tanya Dukes |publisher = Instore, January/February 2014 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171120142739/https://www.instoremag.com/products/399-products-indesign/designer-profiles/12818-designing-lives-paolo-costagli#!AN_572_GIA_Fancy_Light_Yel |archivedate = 2017-11-20 |accessdate=2017-11-20}}</ref> where he took the Graduate Gemologist course at the [[Gemological Institute of America]].<ref name="et">{{cite web |url= http://www.elitetraveler.com/leaders-in-luxury/paolo-costagli |title= Paolo Costagli |author = Douglas Gollan |date = 2012-12-07 |publisher = elitetraveler.com |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130214081015/http://www.elitetraveler.com/leaders-in-luxury/paolo-costagli |archivedate = 2013-02-14 |accessdate=2017-11-15}}</ref><ref name="jl">{{cite web |url = http://www.justluxe.com/fine-living/jewelry/feature-1842640.php |title = City-Inspired Pieces by Italian Jeweler Paolo Costagli |author = Nicolle Keogh |date = 2012-10-22 |publisher = justluxe.com |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121101032909/http://www.justluxe.com/fine-living/jewelry/feature-1842640.php |archivedate = 2012-11-01 |accessdate = 2017-11-15 |deadurl = yes |df = }}</ref> After getting his gemologist degree Costagli went to [[Muzo]], [[Colombia]] and worked for several months at the [[emerald]] mines.<ref name="robb2007">{{cite web |url= http://robbreport.com/style/jewelry/jewelry-treasure-hunter-240329/ |title= Jewelry: Treasure Hunter |author = Jill Newman |date = 2007-08-01 |publisher= [[Robb Report]] |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171117192057/http://robbreport.com/style/jewelry/jewelry-treasure-hunter-240329/ |archivedate = 2017-11-17 |accessdate=2017-11-25}}</ref><ref name="epoch" /> He then moved to [[Bogotá]] and worked there for a Japanese export company specializing in emeralds.<ref name="robb2007" />
==Career== He returned to the United States in 1991<ref name="ny" /> and in 1993 started his own gem and antique jewelry business specializing in colored stones.<ref name="robb2007" /> He was buying signed vintage pieces from known jewelry designers and selling them in the trade.<ref name="instoreint" /> He learned the craft of jewelry making from the designers like [[René Boivin]], [[Suzanne Belperron]] and [[Raymond Templier]].<ref name="dvine" /> In 1995 he started to design his own jewels.<ref name="instoreint" /><ref name="robb2007" /> His early collections include ''Florentine'' (2001) inspired by the vivid colors seen in the [[Giardino dell'Iris]] garden in [[Florence]],<ref name="epoch" /><ref name="dvine">{{cite web |url= http://www.the-dvine.com/2012/06/five-minutes-with-jewellery-designer-paolo-costagli/ |title= Five minutes with Jewellery Designer Paolo Costagli |author = Divia Harilela |date = 2012-06-25 |publisher = the-dvine.com |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120701085640/http://www.the-dvine.com/2012/06/five-minutes-with-jewellery-designer-paolo-costagli/ |archivedate = 2012-07-01 |accessdate=2017-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.betteridge.com/paolo-costagli-peridot-pink-sapphire-florentine-bracelet/p/11161/ |title= Peridot & Pink Sapphire "Florentine" Bracelet |publisher = betteridge.com |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171123112839/https://www.betteridge.com/paolo-costagli-peridot-pink-sapphire-florentine-bracelet/p/11161/ |archivedate = 2017-11-23 |accessdate=2017-11-23}}</ref> and ''Brilliante'' (2003), inspired by a [[tile]] pattern at the [[Doge's Palace]] in [[Venice]].<ref name="forbes">{{cite web |url = https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbeslifestyle/2012/12/05/forbeslife-holiday-gift-guide-december-2012/2/ |title = Serious Impact: The ForbesLife Ultimate Luxury Gift Guide |date = 2012-12-05 |publisher = artfixdaily.com |archiveurl = https://archive.is/20171123120728/https://www.forbes.com/sites/forbeslifestyle/2012/12/05/forbeslife-holiday-gift-guide-december-2012/2/ |archivedate = 2017-11-23 |accessdate = 2017-11-23 |deadurl = yes |df = }}</ref><ref name="epoch" /><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thejewelleryeditor.com/jewellery/article/pixelated-fine-jewellery/ |title= Pixelated jewels have flown the games console to conquer our hearts |author = Åse Anderson |date = 2013-09-15 |publisher= thejewelleryeditor.com |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171118074413/http://www.thejewelleryeditor.com/jewellery/article/pixelated-fine-jewellery/ |archivedate = 2017-11-18 |accessdate=2017-11-18}}</ref>
In 2008 his ''Brillante'' [[bracelet]] was included into the permanent collection of [[Museum of Arts and Design]].<ref name="bmad">{{cite web |url= http://collections.madmuseum.org/objects/6307/brillante-bracelet |title= Paolo Costagli (Italian-American): Brillante Bracelet |publisher= [[Museum of Arts and Design]] |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20171116064619/http://collections.madmuseum.org/objects/6307/brillante-bracelet |archivedate = 2017-11-16 |accessdate=2017-11-16}}</ref>
He is based in [[New York City]].
